[[Category:History of ideas]]

In [[financial mathematics]] and [[stochastic optimization]], the concept of [[risk measure]] is used to quantify the risk involved in a random outcome or risk position. Many risk measures have hitherto been proposed, each having certain characteristics. The '''entropic value-at-risk''' ('''EVaR''') is a [[coherent risk measure]] introduced by Ahmadi-Javid,<ref name=Ahmadi1>{{cite book|last=Ahmadi-Javid|first=Amir|title=An information-theoretic approach to constructing coherent risk measures|year=2011|publisher=Proceedings of IEEE International Symposium on Information Theory|location=St. Petersburg, Russia|pages=2125–2127|doi= 10.1109/ISIT.2011.6033932}}</ref><ref name=Ahmadi2>{{cite journal|last=Ahmadi-Javid|first=Amir|title=Entropic value-at-risk: A new coherent risk measure|journal=Journal of Optimization Theory and Applications|year=2012|volume=155|pages=1105–1123|doi=10.1007/s10957-011-9968-2|issue=3}}</ref> which is an upper bound for the [[value at risk]] (VaR) and the [[conditional value-at-risk]] (CVaR), obtained from the [[Chernoff inequality]]. The EVaR can also be represented by using the concept of [[relative entropy]]. Because of its connection with the VaR and the relative entropy, this risk measure is called "entropic value-at-risk". The EVaR was developed to tackle some computational inefficiencies{{clarify|reason=What inefficiencies?|date=February 2013}} of the CVaR. Getting inspiration from the dual representation of the EVaR, Ahmadi-Javid<ref name="Ahmadi1" /><ref name="Ahmadi2" /> developed a wide class of [[coherent risk measure]]s, called '''[[g-entropic risk measure]]s'''. Both the CVaR and the EVaR are members of this class.
== Definition == Let <math>(\Omega,\mathcal{F},P)</math> be a [[probability space]] with <math>\Omega</math> a set of all simple events, <math>\mathcal{F}</math> a <math>\sigma</math>-algebra of subsets of <math>\Omega</math> and <math>P</math> a [[probability measure]] on <math>\mathcal{F}</math>. Let <math>X</math> be a [[random variable]] and <math>\mathbf{L}_{M^+}</math> be the set of all [[Borel measurable]] functions <math>X:\Omega\to\R</math> whose [[moment-generating function]] <math>M_X(z)</math> exists for all <math>z\geq 0</math>. The entropic value-at-risk (EVaR) of <math>X\in \mathbf{L}_{M^+}</math> with confidence level <math>1-\alpha</math> is defined as follows:
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X):=\inf_{z>0} \left \{z^{-1}\ln \left (\frac{M_X(z)}{\alpha} \right ) \right \}.</math>|{{EquationRef|1}}}}
In finance, the [[random variable]] <math>X \in \mathbf{L}_{M^+},</math> in the above equation, is used to model the ''losses'' of a portfolio.
Consider the Chernoff inequality
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\Pr(X\geq a)\leq e^{-za}M_X(z),\quad \forall z>0.</math>|{{EquationRef|2}}}}
Solving the equation <math> e^{-za}M_X(z)=\alpha</math> for <math>a,</math> results in
:<math>a_X(\alpha,z):=z^{-1}\ln \left (\frac{M_X(z)}{\alpha} \right ).</math>
By considering the equation ({{EquationNote|1}}), we see that
:<math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X):=\inf_{z>0}\{a_X(\alpha,z)\},</math>
which shows the relationship between the EVaR and the Chernoff inequality. It is worth noting that <math>a_X(1,z)</math> is the ''[[entropic risk measure]]'' or ''[[exponential premium]]'', which is a concept used in finance and insurance, respectively.
Let <math>\mathbf{L}_{M}</math> be the set of all Borel measurable functions <math>X:\Omega\to \R</math> whose moment-generating function <math>M_X(z)</math> exists for all <math>z</math>. The [[dual representation]] (or robust representation) of the EVaR is as follows:
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)=\sup_{Q\in \Im}(E_Q(X)),</math>|{{EquationRef|3}}}}
where <math>X\in \mathbf{L}_{M},</math> and <math>\Im</math> is a set of probability measures on <math>(\Omega,\mathcal{F})</math> with <math>\Im=\{Q\ll P:D_{KL}(Q||P)\leq-\ln\alpha\}</math>. Note that
:<math>D_{KL}(Q||P):=\int\frac{dQ}{dP}\left (\ln\frac{dQ}{dP} \right )dP</math>
is the [[relative entropy]] of <math>Q</math> with respect to <math>P,</math> also called the [[Kullback–Leibler divergence]]. The dual representation of the EVaR discloses the reason behind its naming.
==Properties== * The EVaR is a coherent risk measure.
* The moment-generating function <math>M_X(z)</math> can be represented by the EVaR: for all <math>X\in \mathbf{L}_{M^+}</math> and <math>z>0</math> {{NumBlk|::|<math>M_X(z)=\sup_{0<\alpha\leq 1}\{\alpha\exp(z\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X))\}.</math>|{{EquationRef|4}}}}
* For <math>X,Y\in\mathbf{L}_M</math>, <math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)=\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(Y)</math> for all <math>\alpha\in]0,1]</math> if and only if <math>F_X(b)=F_Y(b)</math> for all <math>b\in\R</math>.
* The entropic risk measure with parameter <math>\theta,</math> can be represented by means of the EVaR: for all <math>X\in \mathbf{L}_{M^+}</math> and <math>\theta>0</math> {{NumBlk|::|<math>\theta^{-1}\ln M_X(\theta)=a_X(1,\theta)=\sup_{0<\alpha\leq 1}\{\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)+\theta^{-1}\ln\alpha\}.</math>|{{EquationRef|5}}}}
* The EVaR with confidence level <math>1-\alpha</math> is the tightest possible upper bound that can be obtained from the Chernoff inequality for the VaR and the CVaR with confidence level <math>1 - \alpha</math>; {{NumBlk|::|<math>\text{VaR}(X)\leq \text{CVaR}(X)\leq\text{EVaR}(X).</math>|{{EquationRef|6}}}}
* The following inequality holds for the EVaR: {{NumBlk|::|<math>\text{E}(X)\leq\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)\leq\text{esssup}(X)</math>|{{EquationRef|7}}}} :where <math>\text{E}(X)</math> is the [[expected value]] of <math>X</math> and <math>\text{esssup}(X)</math> is the [[essential supremum]] of <math>X</math>, i.e., <math>\inf_{t\in\R}\{t:\Pr(X\leq t)=1\}</math>. So do hold <math>\text{EVaR}_0(X)=\text{E}(X)</math> and <math>\lim_{\alpha\to 0}\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)=\text{esssup}(X)</math>.
==Examples== [[File:Comparing the VaR, CVaR and EVaR for the standard normal distribution.png|thumbnail|right|Comparing the VaR, CVaR and EVaR for the standard normal distribution]] [[File:Comparing the VaR, CVaR and EVaR for the uniform distribution.png|thumbnail|right|Comparing the VaR, CVaR and EVaR for the uniform distribution over the interval (0,1)]] For <math>X\sim N(\mu,\sigma^2),</math>
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)=\mu+\sigma\sqrt{-2\ln\alpha}.</math>|{{EquationRef|8}}}}
For <math>X\sim U(a,b),</math>
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{EVaR}_{1-\alpha}(X)=\inf_{t>0}\left\lbrace t\ln\left(t\frac{e^{t^{-1}b}-e^{t^{-1}a}}{b-a}\right)-t\ln\alpha \right\rbrace. </math>|{{EquationRef|9}}}}
Figures 1 and 2 show the comparing of the VaR, CVaR and EVaR for <math>N(0,1)</math> and <math>U(0,1)</math>.
==Optimization== Let <math>\rho</math> be a risk measure. Consider the optimization problem
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\min_{\boldsymbol{w}\in \boldsymbol{W}}\rho(G(\boldsymbol{w},\boldsymbol{\psi})),</math>|{{EquationRef|10}}}}
where <math>\boldsymbol{w}\in\boldsymbol{W}\subseteq\R^n</math> is an <math>n</math>-dimensional real [[decision vector]], <math>\boldsymbol{\psi}</math> is an <math>m</math>-dimensional real [[random vector]] with a known [[probability distribution]] and the function <math>G(\boldsymbol{w},.) :\R^m\to\R</math> is a Borel measurable function for all values <math>\boldsymbol{w}\in\boldsymbol{W}.</math> If <math>\rho=\text{EVaR},</math> then the optimization problem ({{EquationNote|10}}) turns into:
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\min_{\boldsymbol{w}\in\boldsymbol{W}, t>0} \left \{t\ln M_{G(\boldsymbol{w},\boldsymbol{\psi})}(t^{-1})-t\ln\alpha \right \}.</math>|{{EquationRef|11}}}}
Let <math>\boldsymbol{S}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}</math> be the [[support of the random vector]] <math>\boldsymbol{\psi}.</math> If <math>G(.,\boldsymbol{s})</math> is [[convex function|convex]] for all <math>\boldsymbol{s}\in\boldsymbol{S}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}</math>, then the objective function of the problem ({{EquationNote|11}}) is also convex. If <math>G(\boldsymbol{w},\boldsymbol{\psi})</math> has the form
{{NumBlk|:|<math>G(\boldsymbol{w},\boldsymbol{\psi})=g_0(\boldsymbol{w})+\sum_{i=1}^mg_i(\boldsymbol{w})\psi_i,\qquad g_i:\R^n\to\R, i=0,1,\ldots,m,</math>|{{EquationRef|12}}}}
and <math>\psi_1,\ldots,\psi_m</math> are [[independent random variables]] in <math>\mathbf{L}_M</math>, then ({{EquationNote|11}}) becomes
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\min_{\boldsymbol{w}\in\boldsymbol{W}, t>0}\left\lbrace g_0(\boldsymbol{w})+t\sum_{i=1}^m\ln M_{g_i(\boldsymbol{w})\psi_i}(t^{-1})-t \ln \alpha \right\rbrace.</math>|{{EquationRef|13}}}}
which is computationally [[tractable problem|tractable]]. But for this case, if one uses the CVaR in problem ({{EquationNote|10}}), then the resulting problem becomes as follows:
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\min_{\boldsymbol{w}\in\boldsymbol{W}, t\in\R}\left\lbrace t+\frac{1}{\alpha}\text{E}\left[ g_0(\boldsymbol{w})+ \sum_{i=1}^{m} g_i(\boldsymbol{w}) \psi_i-t \right]_+ \right\rbrace.</math>|{{EquationRef|14}}}}
It can be shown that by increasing the dimension of <math>\psi</math>, problem ({{EquationNote|14}}) is computationally intractable even for simple cases. For example, assume that <math>\psi_1,\ldots,\psi_m</math> are independent [[discrete random variable]]s that take <math>k</math> distinct values. For fixed values of <math>\boldsymbol{w}</math> and <math>t,</math> the [[complexity]] of computing the objective function given in problem ({{EquationNote|13}}) is of order <math>mk</math> while the computing time for the objective function of problem ({{EquationNote|14}}) is of order <math>k^m</math>. For illustration, assume that <math>k=2, m=100</math> and the summation of two numbers takes <math>10^{-12}</math> seconds. For computing the objective function of problem ({{EquationNote|14}}) one needs about <math>4\times 10^{10}</math> years, whereas the evaluation of objective function of problem ({{EquationNote|13}}) takes about <math>10^{-10}</math> seconds. This shows that formulation with the EVaR outperforms the formulation with the CVaR (see <ref name=Ahmadi2/> for more details).
==Generalization (g-entropic risk measures)== Drawing inspiration from the dual representation of the EVaR given in ({{EquationNote|3}}), one can define a wide class of information-theoretic coherent risk measures, which are introduced in.<ref name=Ahmadi1/><ref name=Ahmadi2/> Let <math>g</math> be a convex [[proper function]] with <math>g(1)=0</math> and <math>\beta</math> be a non-negative number. The <math>g</math>-entropic risk measure with divergence level <math>\beta</math> is defined as
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{ER}_{g,\beta}(X):=\sup_{Q\in\Im}\text{E}_Q(X)</math>|{{EquationRef|15}}}}
where <math>\Im=\{Q\ll P:H_g(P,Q)\leq\beta\}</math> in which <math>H_g(P,Q)</math> is the [[generalized relative entropy]] of <math>Q</math> with respect to <math>P</math>. A primal representation of the class of <math>g</math>-entropic risk measures can be obtained as follows:
{{NumBlk|:|<math>\text{ER}_{g,\beta}(X)=\inf_{t>0,\mu\in\R}\left\lbrace t\left[ \mu+\text{E}_P\left( g^*\left( \frac{X}{t}-\mu+\beta \right) \right) \right] \right\rbrace</math>|{{EquationRef|16}}}}
where <math>g^*</math> is the conjugate of <math>g</math>. By considering
{{NumBlk|:|<math>g(x)=\begin{cases} x\ln x & x>0 \\ 0 & x=0 \\ +\infty & x<0 \end{cases}</math>|{{EquationRef|17}}}}
with <math>g^*(x)=e^{x-1}</math> and <math>\beta=- \ln\alpha</math>, the EVaR formula can be deduced. The CVaR is also a <math>g</math>-entropic risk measure, which can be obtained from ({{EquationNote|16}}) by setting
{{NumBlk|:|<math>g(x)= \begin{cases} 0 & 0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{\alpha} \\ +\infty & \text{otherwise}\end{cases}</math>|{{EquationRef|18}}}}
with <math>g^*(x)=\tfrac{1}{\alpha}\max\{0,x\}</math> and <math>\beta=0</math> (see <ref name=Ahmadi1/><ref name=Ahmadi3>{{cite journal|last=Ahmadi-Javid|first=Amir|title=Addendum to: Entropic Value-at-Risk: A New Coherent Risk Measure|journal=Journal of Optimization Theory and Applications|year=2012|volume=155|pages=1124–1128|doi=10.1007/s10957-012-0014-9|issue=3}}</ref> for more details).
For more results on <math>g</math>-entropic risk measures see.<ref name=Csiszar>{{cite arXiv|last1=Breuer|first1=Thomas|last2=Csiszar |first2=Imre|title=Measuring Distribution Model Risk|eprint=1301.4832v1|year=2013|version=}}</ref>
